I67T1``SEC. 1242. FINDINGS AND DECLARATION OF POLICY.

S5800

I21``(a) T4FindingsK._Congress makes the following findings:

I22``(1) A fair business environment is necessary to advance international trade, economic stability, and development worldwide, is beneficial for American workers and businesses, and is in the United States national interest.

I22``(2) In some cases, mandated offset requirements can cause economic distortions in international defense trade and undermine fairness and competitiveness, and may cause particular harm to small- and medium-sized businesses.

I22``(3) The use of offsets may lead to increasing dependence on foreign suppliers for the production of United States weapons systems.

I22``(4) The offset demands required by some purchasing countries, including some close allies of the United States, equal or exceed the value of the base contract they are intended to offset, mitigating much of the potential economic benefit of the exports.

I22``(5) Offset demands often unduly distort the prices of defense contracts.

I22``(6) In some cases, United States contractors are required to provide indirect offsets which can negatively impact nondefense industrial sectors.

I22``(7) Unilateral efforts by the United States to prohibit offsets may be impractical in the current era of globalization and would severely hinder the competitiveness of the United States defense industry in the global market.

I22``(8) The development of global standards to manage and restrict demands for offsets would enhance United States efforts to mitigate the negative impact of offsets.

I21``(b) T4Declaration of PolicyK._It is the policy of the United States to monitor the use of offsets in international defense trade, to promote fairness in such trade, and to ensure that foreign participation in the production of United States weapons systems does not harm the economy of the United States.

S5804

I67T1``SEC. 1243. DEFINITIONS.

S5800

I21``In this subtitle:

I22``(1) T4Appropriate congressional committeesK._The term `appropriate congressional committees' means_

I23``(A) the Committee on Foreign Relations of the Senate; and

I23``(B) the Committee on International Relations [now Committee on Foreign Affairs] of the House of Representatives.

I22``(2) Gÿ098._The term `Gÿ098' means the group consisting of France, Germany, Japan, the United Kingdom, the United States, Canada, Italy, and Russia established to facilitate economic cooperation among the eight major economic powers.

I22``(3) T4OffsetK._The term `offset' means the entire range of industrial and commercial benefits provided to foreign governments as an inducement or condition to purchase military goods or services, including benefits such as coproduction, licensed production, subcontracting, technology transfer, in-country procurement, marketing and financial assistance, and joint ventures.

I22``(4) T4Transatlantic economic partnershipK._The term `Transatlantic Economic Partnership' means the joint commitment made by the United States and the European Union to reinforce their close relationship through an initiative involving the intensification and extension of multilateral and bilateral cooperation and common actions in the areas of trade and investment.

I22``(5) T4Wassenaar arrangementK._The term `Wassenaar Arrangement' means the multilateral export control regime in which the United States participates that seeks to promote transparency and responsibility with regard to transfers of conventional armaments and sensitive dual-use items.

I22``(6) T4World trade organizationK._The term `World Trade Organization' means the organization established pursuant to the WTO Agreement.

I22``(7) T4WTO agreementK._The term `WTO Agreement' means the Agreement Establishing the World Trade Organization entered into on April 15, 1994.

