I67T1``SEC. 1247. ESTABLISHMENT OF REVIEW COMMISSION.

S5800

I21``(a) T4In GeneralK._There is established a National Commission on the Use of Offsets in Defense Trade (in this section referred to as the `Commission') to address all aspects of the use of offsets in international defense trade.

I21``(b) T4Commission MembershipK._Not later than 120 days after the date of enactment of this Act [Nov. 29, 1999], the President, with the concurrence of the Majority and Minority Leaders of the Senate and the Speaker and Minority Leader of the House of Representatives, shall appoint 11 individuals to serve as members of the Commission. Commission membership shall include_

I22``(1) representatives from the private sector, including_

I23``(A) one each from_

I24``(i) a labor organization,

I24``(ii) a United States defense manufacturing company dependent on foreign sales,

I24``(iii) a United States company dependent on foreign sales that is not a defense manufacturer, and

I24``(iv) a United States company that specializes in international investment, and

I23``(B) two members from academia with widely recognized expertise in international economics; and

I22``(2) five members from the executive branch, including a member from_

I23``(A) the Office of Management and Budget,

I23``(B) the Department of Commerce,

I23``(C) the Department of Defense,

I23``(D) the Department of State, and

I23``(E) the Department of Labor.

I33The member designated from the Office of Management and Budget shall serve as Chairperson of the Commission. The President shall ensure that the Commission is nonpartisan and that the full range of perspectives on the subject of offsets in the defense industry is adequately represented.

I21``(c) T4DutiesK._The Commission shall be responsible for reviewing and reporting on_

I22``(1) the full range of current practices by foreign governments in requiring offsets in purchasing agreements and the extent and nature of offsets offered by United States and foreign defense industry contractors;

I22``(2) the impact of the use of offsets on defense subcontractors and nondefense industrial sectors affected by indirect offsets; and

I22``(3) the role of offsets, both direct and indirect, on domestic industry stability, United States trade competitiveness and national security.

I21``(d) T4Commission ReportK._Not later than 12 months after the Commission is established, the Commission shall submit a report to the appropriate congressional committees. In addition to the items described under subsection (c), the report shall include_

I22``(1) an analysis of_

I23``(A) the collateral impact of offsets on industry sectors that may be different than those of the contractor providing the offsets, including estimates of contracts and jobs lost as well as an assessment of damage to industrial sectors;

I23``(B) the role of offsets with respect to competitiveness of the United States defense industry in international trade and the potential damage to the ability of United States contractors to compete if offsets were prohibited or limited; and

I23``(C) the impact on United States national security, and upon United States nonproliferation objectives, of the use of coproduction, subcontracting, and technology transfer with foreign governments or companies that results from fulfilling offset requirements, with particular emphasis on the question of dependency upon foreign nations for the supply of critical components or technology;

I22``(2) proposals for unilateral, bilateral, or multilateral measures aimed at reducing any detrimental effects of offsets; and

I22``(3) an identification of the appropriate executive branch agencies to be responsible for monitoring the use of offsets in international defense trade.

